As to these things, I shall in the first place assume that the digestion of food is effected by the animal spirits, brought by means ol the nerves, ol which there are many inserted in the stomach, and that according as the animal spirits come to the viscera which serve lor digestion in greater or in smaller abundance, so the digestion ol the food is accomplished more quickly or more slowly. Hence if any one soon after a meal sets himself to study, or thinks much upon a difficult subject, so that the animal spirits are to a great extent detained in the brain on account ol strained contemplation and greater agitation of the mind, the fonction ol digestion is not properly performed on account of the deficiency ol animal spirits; but the undigested food remaining in the stomach produces heaviness and discomfort there, as anyone can observe in his own case. Yet, on the other hand, when the mind is free from thought, or even in sleep, the concoction of food goes on at the best, that is to say, in so far as the animal spirits, not being engaged in carrying on other functionS, are abundantly supplied to the viscera devoted to digestion. This is also indicated by the fact that soon alter a rather full dinner or supper we usually have an inclination to sleep.
